  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 19-26.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - REIGN OF AMON. The short reign of Amen, the son and successor of Manasseh, was distinguished by only two events: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(1)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " his restoration of all the idolatrous and wicked practices which his father had upheld during the earlier portion of his reign; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " his untimely death, in consequence of a conspiracy which was formed against him among the officers of his court. The writer of Kings is therefore able to dispatch his history in eight verses. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 19.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Amon was twenty and two years old when he began to reign.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " So Josephus ('Ant. Jud.,' 10:4. § 1), and the author of Chronicles (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 33:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He must have been born in  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "date",
        "text": "B.C. 664",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", early in the reign of Asshur-bani-pal, probably in the year of that monarch's expedition against Tyro. And he reigned two years in Jerusalem. The \"twelve years\" assigned to Amen By the Duke of Manchester ('Times of Daniel') are wholly devoid of foundation, and would throw the entire chronology into confusion. As it is, there is a very exact accordance in this part of the history between the profane and the scriptural dates. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And his mother's name was Meshullemeth, the daughter of Haruz of Jotbah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Jotbah is probably the same city as the \"Jotbath\" of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 10:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the \"Jotbathah\" of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 33:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which was in the neighborhood of Ezion-geber, and therefore probably in the Arabah. Josephus, however, says that Jot-bah was \"a city of Judah.\" 2 Kings 21:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Reign of Amon (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 33:21-25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - Amon reigned only two years, and that in the spirit of his father, that is to say, worshipping all his idols. The city of Jotbah, from which his mother sprang, was, according to Jerome (in the Onom. s. v. Jethaba), urbs antiqua Judaeae; but it is not further known. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
